Tickets and projects now both filter based on the user accessing them thanks to custom querysets created for both projects and tickets. These querysets filter based on the user's status, but in essence, all they do is filter objects based on whether the user is assigned to the corresponding project. Like so:

```python
class ProjectQueryset(models.QuerySet):
    def filter_for_user(self, user):
        if user.is_staff:
            return Project.objects.all()
        elif user.profile.is_manager:
            return Project.objects.filter(manager=user)
        elif user.profile.is_developer:
            return Project.objects.filter(developers=user)
        return Project.objects.none()

class TicketQueryset(models.QuerySet):
    def filter_for_user(self, user):
        if user.is_staff:
            return Ticket.objects.all()
        elif user.profile.is_manager:
            return Ticket.objects.filter(project__manager=user)
        elif user.profile.is_developer:
            return Ticket.objects.filter(project__developers=user)
        return Project.objects.none()
```
Then I just use this custom `for_user` queryset anytime I call the relevant models in a view.

